Follow-up

If it is possible to construct an accurate WEEKLY payroll report with the ADP granular data ... can we close down the BLS' payroll report efforts?

The complaint, I believe, is that ADP gave the Fed some NON-PUBLIC (more granular) data that they use to reverse-engineer a reasonable-to-good proxy for a WEEKLY payroll report (per the footnote to Waller's August speech).

ADP has been around for nearly 20 years. They charge a lot of money for detailed data, but apparently not for the "secret" granular data the Fed gets.

ADP's monthly payroll estimate, released two days before the payroll report, has become a joke on Wall Street for its high inaccuracy.

Now we learn, supposedly, that ADP has granular data from which a reasonable weekly payroll report can be constructed, which they do not share with the public.
---
If ADP were really interested in the "spirit of public service," it would be concerned about financial markets being mispriced due to a lack of proper data. They would share this granular data weekly with the public to ensure efficient, proper pricing.

Public disclosure and market efficiency are more important than keeping economists at the Fed busy.
